Returns the updated queue configuration.

data.current_description: Leases tasks from a pull queue for lease_duration. This method is invoked by the worker to obtain a lease. The payload is intended to store data that the worker needs to perform the work associated with the task. To return the payloads in the response, set response_view to FULL. A maximum of 10 qps of LeaseTasks requests are allowed per queue. RESOURCE_EXHAUSTED is returned when this limit is exceeded. RESOURCE_EXHAUSTED is also returned when max_tasks_dispatched_per_second is exceeded.

data.description_suggestion: Leases tasks from a pull queue for a specified lease_duration, typically invoked by worker processes. Returns leased tasks with their payloads (set response_view to FULL to include payloads). Workers must call AcknowledgeTask after completing work. Rate limits: maximum 10 requests per second per queue; RESOURCE_EXHAUSTED error returned when this limit or max_tasks_dispatched_per_second is exceeded. Leased tasks are reserved for the worker during the lease period.

data.current_description: Forces a task to run now. When this method is called, Cloud Tasks will dispatch the task, even if the task is already running, the queue has reached its RateLimits or is PAUSED. This command is meant to be used for manual debugging. For example, RunTask can be used to retry a failed task after a fix has been made or to manually force a task to be dispatched now. The dispatched task is returned. That is, the task that is returned contains the status after the task is dispatched but before the task is received by its target. If Cloud Tasks receives a successful response from the task's target, then the task will be deleted; otherwise the task's schedule_time will be reset to the time that RunTask was called plus the retry delay specified in the queue's RetryConfig. RunTask returns NOT_FOUND when it is called on a task that has already succeeded or permanently failed. RunTask cannot be called on a pull task.
data.summary_suggestion: Force immediate task execution
data.description_suggestion: Forces a task to run immediately, bypassing normal queue dispatch rules and rate limits. This method dispatches the task even if it's already running, the queue is paused, or rate limits are reached. Intended for manual debugging and task retry scenarios. Returns the task with dispatch status. If the target responds successfully, the task is deleted; otherwise, schedule_time is reset to current time plus the queue's retry delay. Returns NOT_FOUND for already-succeeded or permanently-failed tasks. Cannot be used on pull-type tasks.
data.reasoning: Missing summary. Description is very long and could be more concise. Reorganized to clarify the override behavior, return conditions, and limitations for better AI agent decision-making about when to use this operation.
